         <lb/>
         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi> POEM <hi rend="small">OF</hi> THE
                                   BROTHERS.<lb/>
            <hi rend="small">note i. </hi>
         </head>
         <div xml:id="note1b">
            <p rend="note">Page 27—line 1. “There were two springs
                                   which bubbled side by side.” The impressive circumstance
                                   here described, actually took place some years ago in this
                                   country, upon an eminence called Kidstow Pike, one of the highest
                                   of the mountains that surround Hawes-water. The summit of the
                                   Pike was stricken by lightning; and every trace of one of the
                                   fountains disappeared, while the other continued to flow as
                                   before.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note ii.</hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 29—line 6. “The thought of death sits
                                   easy on the man,” &amp;c. There is not any thing more
                                   worthy of remark in the manners of the inhabitants of these
                                   mountains, than the tranquillity, I might say indifference, with
                                   which they think and talk upon the subject of death. Some of the
                                   country church-yards, as here described, do not contain a single
                                   tomb-stone, and most of them have a very small number.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
